						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'm not sure it would be the &quot;most common case&quot;</div><br />At the moment, using A13 is - literally - the most common case (as it's used by the magic floor game).<br />And other than that, it's the simpliest/straightest mapping, the thing that first comes to mind to most people when they don't need special tricks. I'd assume A13 will stay quite common for future games. And mind the memory/opcode saving: With A12 you couldn't use address 0000h for CHR-RAM, so A13 does at least have a small advantage.<br /><br />Btw. for non-A13 mappings, there might be in fact one case where programmers may <strong>want to rely</strong> on special mirrors: If you share one 1K block for BOTH name table and char data, then it would make sense to access both in the 2xxxh area, or both in 0xxxh area  (instead of separating CHR at 0xxxh, and NT at 2xxxh).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

